        [32m'<section #results | Results>\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'<section #discussion | Discussion>\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'Features: each section uses the short-form `<tag attrs | content>` pattern. No explicit closing required. When the section-nesting bridge is in place, these become four sibling `<section>` elements in the output HTML.\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'### 5.2. Sections with sub-sections\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'<section #intro | Introduction>\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'Some introductory prose.\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'<sub-section #motivation | Motivation>\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'The motivation is described here.\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'<sub-section #related-work | Related Work>\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'A discussion of related work.\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'<section #methods | Methods>\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'The methods section begins, implicitly ending the related-work sub-section *and* the introduction section.\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'Features: section depth is tracked by the named depth ladder (`section`, `sub-section`, `sub-sub-section`). A new `section` closes any open `sub-section` *and* the previous `section`. A new `sub-section` closes any open `sub-section` but stays inside the current `section`.\n'[39m +
        [32m'\n'[39m +
        [32m'### 5.3. Three-deep section nesting\n'[39m +
